<font color="#FF0000">MARINE CORPS MORAL TRAINING</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 11 19:51:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John <br>
Great post, your commitment to your Christian believes in Vietnam is commendable. In the Marine Corps among the screaming, cussing and all that Gung Ho stuff we were taught to believe in our country, in our God and to practice strong moral behavior. To believe and trust in our fellow Marines, in our leaders and in treating captured and wounded enemies with respect. Issues that the Marine Corps is once again teaching in Marine Basic training. <br><br>
June 1967 <br>
Before boarding the plane for the land of no postage stamps a good Samaritan walked among our ranks handing out small New testament Bibles.<br><br>
From my Diary, Dreams of Glory, Clear Fields of Fire, © Copyright 1997, Cook Barela<br><br>
As I settled into my seat on board the Continental Airlines plane. <br><br>
“I pocketed the small Bible I had been given by the elderly gentleman.  Later,  I would place it in my flak-jacket's outside left breast pocket and carry it there for the duration of  my Viet Nam tour. <br>
Bullet stoppers was what they were called, and some did indeed stop a bullet or shrapnel and thereby saved a Marines life. Besides the cookies, the Bibles and the Kool-Aid, the good Samaritans had uttered some words of encouragement and quoted some scriptures. <br><br>
As I sat back in my seat, I wished that I could remember what the old man had said or know where to find those words in the little black book.”<br><br>
A MONTH LATER.....<br><br>
Hill 65, South Viet Nam<br>
10:00 hours, July 9th, 1967<br><br>
On the 9th of July a Marine Corps Chaplain came to Hill 65 and Christian services were held for those wishing to attend.  Most of us not on duty attended. I don’t remember what he said, but I do remember a new awareness of my vulnerability.<br>
I wasn't religious during my tour of Viet Nam, but I believed in God. I certainly believe there were instances where my life was supernaturally spared. It's hard to explain, but during those moments of potential or extreme danger there were instances of a sudden inner urging, a unique sense of danger, a quickness or awareness and response to a life threatening situation that defies human explanation.<br>
My Christian experiences begin, when My sister, Dominga, took me to a Pentecostal church when I was in high school. I had made a confession of faith and had even been baptized. But my religiousness was based on what my sister and others had told me.  I had not personally examined the scriptures to see if what they said was real. <br>
Over the months that followed, I made a one sided agreement with God to which I tried to stick to religiously. I was still carrying the miniature Bible I had been given by the Good Samaritans in my flak jacket's pocket, but to me it just didn't make much sense.  When I tried to read it, I never got through all the begats in Matthew's gospel.  So, I would just place it back in my pocket and practice my own form of  religion. <br><br>
If God got me out of a tight situation where I might have gotten killed or wounded, then I felt I sort of owed Him one and so in repayment I would go to the church services provided for us, that is if they were available, and if I could. If no such services were offered, I said the Lord's prayer. I said that prayer often, especially on a chopper before landing in hot LZ’s.<br>
 <br>
Sometimes if I went to the church services and I hadn’t been in a dangerous situation then I figured God owed me one, and so it went. I even promised Him that if He got me back home, I would go to church every Sunday, if fact I said that I would go to church twice every Sunday, but when I returned home, I never did.<br><br>
Ten years later I was converted. Two and a half years after that, I was ordained a Christian minister. The Senior Pastor and my mentor in the church that ordained me was a converted Jew. Joseph Arron Lessin, a book was written about him, “Gone the Golden Dream,” Bethany Press. <br>
I guess God does have a sense of humor and he always collects<br>

